# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vba-macros
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vba-macros/api-overview] Access to this page requires authorization.
[src:vba-macros/api-overview] You can try signing in or changing directories.
[src:vba-macros/api-overview] Office Visual Basic for Applications (VBA) is an event-driven programming language that enables you to extend Office applications.
[src:vba-macros/api-overview] This reference is for experienced Office users who want to learn about VBA and who want some insight into how programming can help them to customize Office.
[src:vba-macros/api-overview] The Office suite of applications has a full set of features.
[src:vba-macros/api-overview] There are many different ways to author, format, and manipulate documents, email, databases, forms, spreadsheets, and presentations.
[src:vba-macros/api-overview] The great power of VBA programming in Office is that nearly every operation that you can perform with a mouse, keyboard, or a dialog box can also be automated by using VBA.
[src:vba-macros/api-overview] Further, if it can be done once with VBA, it can be done just as easily a hundred times.
[src:vba-macros/api-overview] In fact, the automation of repetitive tasks is one of the most common uses of VBA in Office.
[src:vba-macros/api-overview] Beyond the power of scripting VBA to accelerate every-day tasks, you can use VBA to add new functionality to Office applications or to prompt and interact with the user of your documents in ways that are specific to your business needs.
[src:vba-macros/api-overview] For example, you could write some VBA code that displays a pop up message that reminds users to save a document to a particular network drive the first time they try to save it.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] In computer programming, a **macro** (short for "**macro instruction**"; from Greek μακρο*-* 'long, large') is a rule or pattern that specifies how a certain input should be mapped to a replacement output.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Applying a macro to an input is known as **macro expansion**.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] The input and output may be a sequence of lexical tokens or characters, or a syntax tree.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Character macros are supported in software applications to make it easy to invoke common command sequences.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Token and tree macros are supported in some programming languages to enable code reuse or to extend the language, sometimes for domain-specific languages.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Macros are used to make a sequence of computing instructions available to the programmer as a single program statement, making the programming task less tedious and less error-prone.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Thus, they are called "macros" because a "big" block of code can be expanded from a "small" sequence of characters.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Macros often allow positional or keyword parameters that dictate what the conditional assembler program generates and have been used to create entire programs or program suites according to such variables as operating system, platform or other factors.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] The term derives from "macro instruction", and such expansions were originally used in generating assembly language code.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] During the 1980s, macro programs – originally SmartKey, then SuperKey, KeyWorks, Prokey – were very popular, first as a means to automatically format screenplays, then for a variety of user-input tasks.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] These programs were based on the terminate-and-stay-resident mode of operation and applied to all keyboard input, no matter in which context it occurred.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] They have to some extent fallen into obsolescence following the advent of mouse-driven user interfaces and the availability of keyboard and mouse macros in applications, such as word processors and spreadsheets, making it possible to create application-sensitive keyboard macros.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Keyboard macros can be used in massively multiplayer online role-playing games (MMORPGs) to perform repetitive, but lucrative tasks, thus accumulating resources.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] As this is done without human effort, it can skew the economy of the game.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] For this reason, use of macros is a violation of the TOS or EULA of most MMORPGs, and their administrators spend considerable effort to suppress them.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Keyboard and mouse macros that are created using an application's built-in macro features are sometimes called **application macros**.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] They are created by carrying out the sequence once and letting the application record the actions.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] An underlying macro programming language, most commonly a scripting language, with direct access to the features of the application may also exist.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] The programmers' text editor Emacs (short for "editing macros") follows this idea to a conclusion.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] In effect, most of the editor is made of macros.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Emacs was originally devised as a set of macros in the editing language TECO; it was later ported to dialects of Lisp.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Another programmers' text editor, Vim (a descendant of vi), also has an implementation of keyboard macros.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] It can record into a register (macro) what a person types on the keyboard and it can be replayed or edited just like VBA macros for Microsoft Office.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Vim also has a scripting language called Vimscript to create macros.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Visual Basic for Applications (VBA) is a programming language included in Microsoft Office from Office 97 through Office 2019 (although it was available in some components of Office prior to Office 97).
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] However, its function has evolved from and replaced the macro languages that were originally included in some of these applications.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] XEDIT, running on the Conversational Monitor System (CMS) component of VM, supports macros written in EXEC, EXEC2 and REXX, and some CMS commands were actually wrappers around XEDIT macros.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] The Hessling Editor (THE), a partial clone of XEDIT, supports Rexx macros using Regina and Open Object REXX (oorexx).
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Many common applications, and some on PCs, use Rexx as a scripting language.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] VBA has access to most Microsoft Windows system calls and executes when documents are opened.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] This makes it relatively easy to write computer viruses in VBA, commonly known as macro viruses.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] In the mid-to-late 1990s, this became one of the most common types of computer virus.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] However, during the late 1990s and to date, Microsoft has been patching and updating its programs.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] In addition, current anti-virus programs immediately counteract such attacks.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] A **parameterized macro** is a macro that is able to insert given objects into its expansion.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] This gives the macro some of the power of a function.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] This causes `PI` to always be replaced with `3.14159` wherever it occurs.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] What this macro expands to depends on what argument *x* is passed to it.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Parameterized macros are a useful source-level mechanism for performing in-line expansion, but in languages such as C where they use simple textual substitution, they have a number of severe disadvantages over other mechanisms for performing in-line expansion, such as inline functions.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] The parameterized macros used in languages such as Lisp, PL/I and Scheme, on the other hand, are much more powerful, able to make decisions about what code to produce based on their arguments; thus, they can effectively be used to perform run-time code generation.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Languages such as C and some assembly languages have rudimentary macro systems, implemented as preprocessors to the compiler or assembler.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] C preprocessor macros work by simple textual substitution at the token, rather than the character level.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] However, the macro facilities of more sophisticated assemblers, e.g., IBM High Level Assembler (HLASM) can't be implemented with a preprocessor; the code for assembling instructions and data is interspersed with the code for assembling macro invocations.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] A classic use of macros is in the computer typesetting system TeX and its derivatives, where most functionality is based on macros.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] MacroML is an experimental system that seeks to reconcile static typing and macro systems.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Nemerle has typed syntax macros, and one productive way to think of these syntax macros is as a multi-stage computation.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Some major applications have been written as text macro invoked by other applications, e.g., by XEDIT in CMS.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Some languages, such as PHP, can be embedded in free-format text, or the source code of other languages.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] The mechanism by which the code fragments are recognised (for instance, being bracketed by `<?php` and `?>`) is similar to a textual macro language, but they are much more powerful, fully featured languages.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Macros in the PL/I language are written in a subset of PL/I itself: the compiler executes "preprocessor statements" at compilation time, and the output of this execution forms part of the code that is compiled.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] The ability to use a familiar procedural language as the macro language gives power much greater than that of text substitution macros, at the expense of a larger and slower compiler.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Macros in PL/I, as well as in many assemblers, may have side effects, e.g., setting variables that other macros can access.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Frame technology's frame macros have their own command syntax but can also contain text in any language.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Each frame is both a generic component in a hierarchy of nested subassemblies, and a procedure for integrating itself with its subassembly frames (a recursive process that resolves integration conflicts in favor of higher level subassemblies).
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] The outputs are custom documents, typically compilable source modules.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Frame technology can avoid the proliferation of similar but subtly different components, an issue that has plagued software development since the invention of macros and subroutines.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Most assembly languages have less powerful procedural macro facilities, for example allowing a block of code to be repeated N times for loop unrolling; but these have a completely different syntax from the actual assembly language.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Macro systems—such as the C preprocessor described earlier—that work at the level of lexical tokens cannot preserve the lexical structure reliably.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Syntactic macro systems work instead at the level of abstract syntax trees, and preserve the lexical structure of the original program.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] The most widely used implementations of syntactic macro systems are found in Lisp-like languages.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] These languages are especially suited for this style of macro due to their uniform, parenthesized syntax (known as S-expressions).
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] In particular, uniform syntax makes it easier to determine the invocations of macros.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Lisp macros transform the program structure itself, with the full language available to express such transformations.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] While syntactic macros are often found in Lisp-like languages, they are also available in other languages such as Prolog, Erlang, Dylan, Scala, Nemerle, Rust, Elixir, Nim, Haxe, and Julia.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] They are also available as third-party extensions to JavaScript and C#.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Before Lisp had macros, it had so-called FEXPRs, function-like operators whose inputs were not the values computed by the arguments but rather the syntactic forms of the arguments, and whose output were values to be used in the computation.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] In other words, FEXPRs were implemented at the same level as EVAL, and provided a window into the meta-evaluation layer.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] This was generally found to be a difficult model to reason about effectively.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] In 1963, Timothy Hart proposed adding macros to Lisp 1.5 in AI Memo 57: MACRO Definitions for LISP.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] An anaphoric macro is a type of programming macro that deliberately captures some form supplied to the macro which may be referred to by an anaphor (an expression referring to another).
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Anaphoric macros first appeared in Paul Graham's On Lisp and their name is a reference to linguistic anaphora—the use of words as a substitute for preceding words.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Hygienic macros have been standardized for Scheme in the R5RS, R6RS, and R7RS standards.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] A number of competing implementations of hygienic macros exist such as `syntax-rules`, `syntax-case`, explicit renaming, and syntactic closures.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Both `syntax-rules` and `syntax-case` have been standardized in the Scheme standards.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Recently, Racket has combined the notions of hygienic macros with a "tower of evaluators", so that the syntactic expansion time of one macro system is the ordinary runtime of another block of code, and showed how to apply interleaved expansion and parsing in a non-parenthesized language.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] A number of languages other than Scheme either implement hygienic macros or implement partially hygienic systems.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Examples include Scala, Rust, Elixir, Julia, Dylan, Nim, and Nemerle.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] ) enables the creation of new syntactic constructs (e.g.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] ) indistinguishable from those built into the language.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] , it is possible to define the latter in terms of the former using macros.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] and hygienic macros, which enables a programmer to design their own control abstractions, such as looping and early exit constructs, without the need to build them into the language.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] can be implemented in a way that is both natural and efficient.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Macros can also be used to introduce new binding constructs.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] into the application of a function to a set of arguments.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Felleisen conjectures that these three categories make up the primary legitimate uses of macros in such a system.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Others have proposed alternative uses of macros, such as anaphoric macros in macro systems that are unhygienic or allow selective unhygienic transformation.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] The interaction of macros and other language features has been a productive area of research.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] For example, components and modules are useful for large-scale programming, but the interaction of macros and these other constructs must be defined for their use together.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Module and component-systems that can interact with macros have been proposed for Scheme and other languages with macros.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] For example, the Racket language extends the notion of a macro system to a syntactic tower, where macros can be written in languages including macros, using hygiene to ensure that syntactic layers are distinct and allowing modules to export macros to other modules.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Macros are normally used to map a short string (macro invocation) to a longer sequence of instructions.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Another, less common, use of macros is to do the reverse: to map a sequence of instructions to a macro string.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] This was the approach taken by the STAGE2 Mobile Programming System, which used a rudimentary macro compiler (called SIMCMP) to map the specific instruction set of a given computer into *machine-independent* macros.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Applications (notably compilers) written in these machine-independent macros can then be run without change on any computer equipped with the rudimentary macro compiler.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] The first application run in such a context is a more sophisticated and powerful macro compiler, written in the machine-independent macro language.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] This macro compiler is applied to itself, in a bootstrap fashion, to produce a compiled and much more efficient version of itself.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] The advantage of this approach is that complex applications can be ported from one computer to a very different computer with very little effort (for each target machine architecture, just the writing of the rudimentary macro compiler).
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] The advent of modern programming languages, notably C, for which compilers are available on virtually all computers, has rendered such an approach superfluous.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] This was, however, one of the first instances (if not the first) of compiler bootstrapping.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] A macro instruction embedded in the otherwise assembly source code would be processed by a macro compiler, a preprocessor to the assembler, to replace the macro with one or more assembly instructions.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] The resulting code, pure assembly, would be translated to machine code by the assembler.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Two of the earliest programming installations to develop macro languages for the IBM 705 computer were at Dow Chemical Corp. in Delaware and the Air Material Command, Ballistics Missile Logistics Office in California.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Some consider macro instructions as an intermediate step between assembly language programming and the high-level programming languages that followed, such as FORTRAN and COBOL.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] By the late 1950s the macro language was followed by the Macro Assemblers.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] This was a combination of both where one program served both functions, that of a macro pre-processor and an assembler in the same package.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Early examples are FORTRAN Assembly Program (FAP) and Macro Assembly Program (IBMAP) on the IBM 709, 7094, 7040 and 7044, and Autocoder on the 7070/7072/7074.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Eastwood and Douglas McIlroy of Bell Labs introduced conditional and recursive macros into the popular SAP assembler, creating what is known as Macro SAP.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] McIlroy's 1960 paper was seminal in the area of extending any (including high-level) programming languages through macro processors.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Macro Assemblers allowed assembly language programmers to implement their own macro-language and allowed limited portability of code between two machines running the same CPU but different operating systems, for example, early versions of MS-DOS and CP/M-86.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] The macro library would need to be written for each target machine but not the overall assembly language program.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Note that more powerful macro assemblers allowed use of conditional assembly constructs in macro instructions that could generate different code on different machines or different operating systems, reducing the need for multiple libraries.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] In the 1980s and early 1990s, desktop PCs were only running at a few MHz and assembly language routines were commonly used to speed up programs written in C, Fortran, Pascal and others.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] These languages, at the time, used different calling conventions.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Macros could be used to interface routines written in assembly language to the front end of applications written in almost any language.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Again, the basic assembly language code remained the same, only the macro libraries needed to be written for each target language.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] In modern operating systems such as Unix and its derivatives, operating system access is provided through subroutines, usually provided by dynamic libraries.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] High-level languages such as C offer comprehensive access to operating system functions, obviating the need for assembler language programs for such functionality.
[src:vba-macros/macro-computer-science] Moreover, standard libraries of several newer programming languages, such as Go, actively discourage the use of syscalls in favor of platform-agnostic libraries as well if not necessary, to improve portability and security.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Excel forms part of the Microsoft 365 and Microsoft Office suites of software and has been developed since 1985.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Microsoft Excel has the basic features of all spreadsheets, using a grid of *cells* arranged in numbered *rows* and letter-named *columns* to organize data manipulations like arithmetic operations.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] It has a battery of supplied functions to answer statistical, engineering, and financial needs.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] In addition, it can display data as line graphs, histograms and charts, and with a very limited three-dimensional graphical display.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] It allows sectioning of data to view its dependencies on various factors for different perspectives (using *pivot tables* and the *scenario manager*).
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] A PivotTable is a tool for data analysis.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] It does this by simplifying large data sets via PivotTable fields.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] It has a programming aspect, *Visual Basic for Applications*, allowing the user to employ a wide variety of numerical methods, for example, for solving differential equations of mathematical physics, and then reporting the results back to the spreadsheet.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] In a more elaborate realization, an Excel application can automatically poll external databases and measuring instruments using an update schedule, analyze the results, make a Word report or PowerPoint slide show, and email these presentations on a regular basis to a list of participants.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Microsoft allows for a number of optional command-line switches to control the manner in which Excel starts.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Of these, 360 existed prior to Excel 2010.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Microsoft classifies these functions into 14 categories.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Of the 484 current functions, 386 may be called from VBA as methods of the object "WorksheetFunction" and 44 have the same names as VBA functions.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] With the introduction of LAMBDA on December 3, 2020, Excel became Turing complete.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] The Windows version of Excel supports programming through Microsoft's Visual Basic for Applications (VBA), which is a dialect of Visual Basic.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Programming with VBA allows spreadsheet manipulation that is awkward or impossible with standard spreadsheet techniques.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Programmers may write code directly using the Visual Basic Editor (VBE), which includes a window for writing code, debugging code, and code module organization environment.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] The user can implement numerical methods as well as automating tasks such as formatting or data organization in VBA and guide the calculation using any desired intermediate results reported back to the spreadsheet.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] VBA was removed from Mac Excel 2008, as the developers did not believe that a timely release would allow porting the VBA engine natively to Mac OS X.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] VBA was restored in the next version, Mac Excel 2011, although the build lacks support for ActiveX objects, impacting some high level developer tools.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] A common and easy way to generate VBA code is by using the Macro Recorder.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] The Macro Recorder records actions of the user and generates VBA code in the form of a macro.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] These actions can then be repeated automatically by running the macro.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] The macros can also be linked to different trigger types like keyboard shortcuts, a command button or a graphic.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] The actions in the macro can be executed from these trigger types or from the generic toolbar options.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] The VBA code of the macro can also be edited in the VBE.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Certain features such as loop functions and screen prompt by their own properties, and some graphical display items, cannot be recorded but must be entered into the VBA module directly by the programmer.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Advanced users can employ user prompts to create an interactive program, or react to events such as sheets being loaded or changed.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Macro Recorded code may not be compatible with all Excel versions.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Some code that is used in Excel 2010 cannot be used in Excel 2003.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Making a Macro that changes the cell colors and making changes to other aspects of cells may not be backward compatible.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] User-created VBA subroutines execute these actions and operate like macros generated using the macro recorder, but are more flexible and efficient.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] From its first version Excel supported end-user programming of macros (automation of repetitive tasks) and user-defined functions (extension of Excel's built-in function library).
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] In early versions of Excel, these programs were written in a macro language whose statements had formula syntax and resided in the cells of special-purpose macro sheets (stored with file extension .XLM in Windows.) XLM was the default macro language for Excel through Excel 4.0.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Beginning with version 5.0 Excel recorded macros in VBA by default but with version 5.0 XLM recording was still allowed as an option.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] After version 5.0 that option was discontinued.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] All versions of Excel, including Excel 2021, are capable of running an XLM macro, though Microsoft discourages their use.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] In 2023, Microsoft announced Excel would support the Python programming language directly.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] As of 2025, Python in Excel is available to Enterprise and Business users (with some exceptions, and is in preview for Family, Personal, and Education users).
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Excel supports charts, graphs, or histograms generated from specified groups of cells.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] It also supports Pivot Charts that allow for a chart to be linked directly to a Pivot table.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] This allows the chart to be refreshed with the Pivot Table.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] The generated graphic component can either be embedded within the current sheet or added as a separate object.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] These displays are dynamically updated if the content of cells changes.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] For example, suppose that the important design requirements are displayed visually; then, in response to a user's change in trial values for parameters, the curves describing the design change shape, and their points of intersection shift, assisting the selection of the best design.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Additional features are available using add-ins.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Versions of Excel up to 7.0 had a limitation in the size of their data sets of 16K (214 = 16384) rows.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Version 12.0 onwards, including the current Version 16.x, can handle over 1M (220 = 1048576) rows, and 16384 (214, labeled as column 'XFD') columns.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Up until the 2007 version, Microsoft Excel used a proprietary binary file format called Excel Binary File Format (.XLS) as its primary format.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Excel 2007 uses Office Open XML as its primary file format, an XML-based format that followed after a previous XML-based format called "XML Spreadsheet" ("XMLSS"), first introduced in Excel 2002.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Although supporting and encouraging the use of new XML-based formats as replacements, Excel 2007 remained backwards-compatible with the traditional, binary formats.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] In addition, most versions of Microsoft Excel can read CSV, DBF, SYLK, DIF, and other legacy formats.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Support for some older file formats, mostly from DOS-based programs, was removed in Excel 2007.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] OpenOffice.org has created documentation of the Excel format.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Two epochs of the format exist: the 97-2003 OLE format, and the older stream format.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Microsoft has made the Excel binary format specification available to freely download.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] The *XML Spreadsheet* format introduced in Excel 2002 is a simple, XML based format missing some more advanced features like storage of VBA macros.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Though the intended file extension for this format is *.xml*, the program also correctly handles XML files with *.xls* extension.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] This feature is widely used by third-party applications (e.g.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] *MySQL Query Browser*) to offer "export to Excel" capabilities without implementing binary file format.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Microsoft Excel 2007, along with the other products in the Microsoft Office 2007 suite, introduced new file formats.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] The first of these (.xlsx) is defined in the Office Open XML (OOXML) specification.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Windows applications such as Microsoft Access and Microsoft Word, as well as Excel can communicate with each other and use each other's capabilities.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] The most common is Dynamic Data Exchange: although strongly deprecated by Microsoft, this is a common method to send data between applications running on Windows, with official MS publications referring to it as "the protocol from hell".
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] As the name suggests, it allows applications to supply data to others for calculation and display.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] It is very common in financial markets, being used to connect to important financial data services such as Bloomberg and Reuters.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] OLE Object Linking and Embedding allows a Windows application to control another to enable it to format or calculate data.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] This may take on the form of "embedding" where an application uses another to handle a task that it is more suited to, for example a PowerPoint presentation may be embedded in an Excel spreadsheet or vice versa.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Excel users can access external data sources via Microsoft Office features such as (for example) `.odc` connections built with the Office Data Connection file format.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Excel files themselves may be updated using a Microsoft supplied ODBC driver.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Excel can accept data in real-time through several programming interfaces, which allow it to communicate with many data sources such as Bloomberg and Reuters (through addins such as Power Plus Pro).
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Alternatively, Microsoft Query provides ODBC-based browsing within Microsoft Excel.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Programmers have produced APIs to open Excel spreadsheets in a variety of applications and environments other than Microsoft Excel.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] These include opening Excel documents on the web using either ActiveX controls, or plugins like the Adobe Flash Player.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] The Apache POI open-source project provides Java libraries for reading and writing Excel spreadsheet files.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] All passwords except *password to open a document* can be removed instantly regardless of the Microsoft Excel version used to create the document.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] These types of passwords are used primarily for shared work on a document.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Such password-protected documents are not encrypted, and data sources from a set password are saved in a document's header.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] *Password to protect workbook* is an exception – when it is set, a document is encrypted with the standard password "VelvetSweatshop", but since it is known to the public, it actually does not add any extra protection to the document.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] The only type of password that can prevent a trespasser from gaining access to a document is the *password to open a document*.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] The cryptographic strength of this kind of protection depends strongly on the Microsoft Excel version that was used to create the document.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] In *Microsoft Excel 95* and earlier versions, the password to open is converted to a 16-bit key that can be instantly cracked.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] In *Excel 97/2000* the password is converted to a 40-bit key, which can also be cracked very quickly using modern equipment.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] As regards services that use rainbow tables (e.g.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Password-Find), it takes up to several seconds to remove protection.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] In addition, password-cracking programs can brute-force attack passwords at a rate of hundreds of thousands of passwords a second, which not only lets them decrypt a document but also find the original password.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] In *Excel 2003/XP* the encryption is slightly better – a user can choose any encryption algorithm that is available in the system (see Cryptographic Service Provider).
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Due to the CSP, an *Excel* file cannot be decrypted, and thus the *password to open* cannot be removed, though the brute-force attack speed remains quite high.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Nevertheless, the older *Excel 97/2000* algorithm is set by the default.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Therefore, users who do not change the default settings lack reliable protection of their documents.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] The situation changed fundamentally in *Excel 2007*, where the modern AES algorithm with a key of 128 bits started being used for decryption, and a 50,000-fold use of the hash function SHA1 reduced the speed of brute-force attacks down to hundreds of passwords per second.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] In *Excel 2010*, the strength of the protection by the default was increased two times due to the use of a 100,000-fold SHA1 to convert a password to a key.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Excel Mobile is a spreadsheet program that can edit XLSX files.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] It can edit and format text in cells, calculate formulas, search within the spreadsheet, sort rows and columns, freeze panes, filter the columns, add comments, and create charts.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] It cannot add columns or rows except at the edge of the document, rearrange columns or rows, delete rows or columns, or add spreadsheet tabs.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] The 2007 version has the ability to use a full-screen mode to deal with limited screen resolution, as well as split panes to view different parts of a worksheet at one time.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Protection settings, zoom settings, autofilter settings, certain chart formatting, hidden sheets, and other features are not supported on Excel Mobile, and will be modified upon opening and saving a workbook.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] In 2015, Excel Mobile became available for Windows 10 and Windows 10 Mobile on Windows Store.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Excel for the web is a free lightweight version of Microsoft Excel available as part of Office on the web, which also includes web versions of Microsoft Word and Microsoft PowerPoint.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Excel for the web can display most of the features available in the desktop versions of Excel, although it may not be able to insert or edit them.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Certain data connections are not accessible on Excel for the web, including with charts that may use these external connections.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Excel for the web also cannot display legacy features, such as Excel 4.0 macros or Excel 5.0 dialog sheets.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] There are also small differences between how some of the Excel functions work.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Microsoft Excel Viewer was a freeware program for Microsoft Windows for viewing and printing spreadsheet documents created by Excel.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Microsoft retired the viewer in April 2018 with the last security update released in February 2019 for Excel Viewer 2007 (SP3).
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] The first version released by Microsoft was Excel 97 Viewer.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Excel 97 Viewer was supported in Windows CE for Handheld PCs.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] In October 2004, Microsoft released Excel Viewer 2003.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] In September 2007, Microsoft released Excel Viewer 2003 Service Pack 3 (SP3).
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] In January 2008, Microsoft released Excel Viewer 2007 (featuring a non-collapsible Ribbon interface).
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] In April 2009, Microsoft released Excel Viewer 2007 Service Pack 2 (SP2).
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] In October 2011, Microsoft released Excel Viewer 2007 Service Pack 3 (SP3).
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Microsoft advises those who wish to view and print Excel files for free to use the Excel Mobile application for Windows 10 and for Windows 7 and Windows 8 to upload the file to OneDrive and use Excel for the web with a Microsoft account to open them in a browser.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] In addition to issues with spreadsheets in general, other problems specific to Excel include numeric precision, misleading statistics functions, mod function errors, date limitations and more.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Despite the use of 15-figure precision, Excel can display many more figures (up to thirty) upon user request.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] But the displayed figures are *not* those actually used in its computations, and so, for example, the difference of two numbers may differ from the difference of their displayed values.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Although such departures are usually beyond the 15th decimal, exceptions do occur, especially for very large or very small numbers.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Serious errors can occur if decisions are made based upon automated comparisons of numbers (for example, using the Excel *If* function), as equality of two numbers can be unpredictable.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] In the figure, the fraction 1/9000 is displayed in Excel.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Although this number has a decimal representation that is an infinite string of ones, Excel displays only the leading 15 figures.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] In the second line, the number one is added to the fraction, and again Excel displays only 15 figures.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] In the third line, one is subtracted from the sum using Excel.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Because the sum in the second line has only eleven 1's after the decimal, the difference when 1 is subtracted from this displayed value is three 0's followed by a string of eleven 1's.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] However, the difference reported by Excel in the third line is three 0's followed by a string of *thirteen* 1's and two extra erroneous digits.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] This is because Excel calculates with about half a digit more than it displays.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Excel works with a modified 1985 version of the IEEE 754 specification.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Excel's implementation involves conversions between binary and decimal representations, leading to accuracy that is on average better than one would expect from simple fifteen digit precision, but that can be worse.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Besides accuracy in user computations, the question of accuracy in Excel-provided functions may be raised.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Particularly in the arena of statistical functions, Excel has been criticized for sacrificing accuracy for speed of calculation.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] As many calculations in Excel are executed using VBA, an additional issue is the accuracy of VBA, which varies with variable type and user-requested precision.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Microsoft has announced that some of these issues are addressed in Excel 2010.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Excel has issues with modulo operations.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] In the case of excessively large results, Excel will return the error warning #NUM! instead of an answer.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Excel includes February 29, 1900, incorrectly treating 1900 as a leap year, even though e.g.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] 2100 is correctly treated as a non-leap year.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Thus, a formula counting dates between (for example) February 1, 1900 and March 1, 1900 will return an incorrect result.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] The bug originated from Lotus 1-2-3, where it was deliberately implemented to save computer memory, and was also intentionally implemented in Excel for the purpose of bug compatibility.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] This legacy has later been carried over into Office Open XML file format.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Excel supports dates with years in the range 1900–9999, except that December 31, 1899, can be entered as 0 and is displayed as 0-jan-1900.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Converting a fraction of a day into hours, minutes and days by treating it as a moment on the day January 1, 1900, does not work for a negative fraction.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] If text is entered that happens to be in a form that Excel interprets as a date, the text can be unintentionally changed to a standard date format.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] A similar problem occurs when a text happens to be in the form of a floating-point notation of a number.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] In these cases the original exact text cannot be recovered from the result.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Formatting the cell as TEXT before entering ambiguous text prevents Excel from converting it.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] This issue has caused a well known problem in the analysis of DNA, for example in bioinformatics.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] As first reported in 2004, genetic scientists found that Excel automatically and incorrectly converts certain gene names into dates.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] For example, MARCH1 (Membrane Associated Ring-CH-type finger 1) gets converted to the date March 1 (1-Mar) and SEPT2 (Septin 2) is converted into September 2 (2-Sep) etc.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] While some secondary news sources reported this as a fault with Excel, the original authors of the 2016 paper placed the blame with the researchers misusing Excel.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] In October 2023, Microsoft introduced a settings option that allows the conversion to be disabled.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] A document with the name '%s' is already open.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] You cannot open two documents with the same name, even if the documents are in different folders.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] To open the second document, either close the document that is currently open, or rename one of the documents.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] The reason is for calculation ambiguity with linked cells.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] If there is a cell `='[Book1.xlsx]Sheet1'!$G$33`, and there are two books named "Book1" open, there is no way to tell which one the user means.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] In 1982, Microsoft launched its first spreadsheet program, Multiplan, which gained popularity on CP/M systems.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] However, Multiplan struggled to compete on MS-DOS systems, losing market share to Lotus 1-2-3, which became the dominant spreadsheet program by 1983, surpassing both Multiplan and the earlier VisiCalc.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] To address Multiplan's falling marketshare, Microsoft began developing a new, advanced spreadsheet program in 1983, codenamed "Odyssey." The project was led by Jabe Blumenthal, who worked on its design, and Doug Klunder, the primary developer of Multiplan.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Originally intended for IBM PCs running CP/M and MS-DOS, the project shifted focus in early 1984 when Lotus began developing Jazz, an integrated program for the Apple Macintosh, and Lotus 1-2-3 maintained its dominance on IBM PCs.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] In March 1984, Bill Gates redirected Odyssey's development to the Macintosh platform, which required supporting the system's 512 KB memory.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] This decision delayed the project by nine months, after which Klunder temporarily left Microsoft to work growing lettuce, and the project then was led by Philip Florence, a former developer at Wang Laboratories.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] After Florence had a heart attack, Klunder returned to finish the project.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] On May 2, 1985, Steve Jobs of Apple Computer and Bill Gates held a joint press conference at Tavern on the Green in New York City to publicly announce Excel for Apple's Macintosh platform.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Following the announcement, the software was officially released for sale on September 30, 1985.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] The first Windows version, Excel 2.05, followed on November 19, 1987, designed to align with the Macintosh version 2.2.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] A 1990 American Institute of Certified Public Accountants member survey found that 2% of respondents used Excel as their spreadsheet, 3% as their database, and 8% for graphics.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Lotus was slow to bring 1-2-3 to Windows and by the early 1990s, Excel had started to outsell 1-2-3 and helped Microsoft achieve its position as a leading PC software developer.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] This accomplishment solidified Microsoft as a valid competitor and showed its future in developing GUI software.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Microsoft maintained its advantage with regular new releases, every two years or so.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Excel 2.0 is the first version of Excel for the Intel platform.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Versions prior to 2.0 were only available on the Apple Macintosh.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] The first Windows version was labeled "2" to correspond to the Mac version.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] It was announced on October 6, 1987, and released on November 19.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] This included a runtime version of Windows.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Included toolbars, drawing capabilities, outlining, add-in support, 3D charts, and many more new features.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Included with Microsoft Office 3.0, this version introduced auto-fill.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Also, an easter egg in Excel 4.0 reveals a hidden animation of a dancing set of numbers 1 through 3, representing Lotus 1–2–3, which is then crushed by an Excel logo.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] With version 5.0, included in Microsoft Office 4.2 and 4.3, Excel included Visual Basic for Applications (VBA), a programming language based on Visual Basic which adds the ability to automate tasks in Excel and to provide user-defined functions (UDF) for use in worksheets.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] VBA includes a fully featured integrated development environment (IDE).
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Macro recording can produce VBA code replicating user actions, thus allowing simple automation of regular tasks.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] VBA allows the creation of forms and in‑worksheet controls to communicate with the user.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] The language supports use (but not creation) of ActiveX (COM) DLL's; later versions add support for class modules allowing the use of basic object-oriented programming techniques.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] The automation functionality provided by VBA made Excel a target for macro viruses.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] This caused serious problems until antivirus products began to detect these viruses.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Microsoft belatedly took steps to prevent the misuse by adding the ability to disable macros completely, to enable macros when opening a workbook or to trust all macros signed using a trusted certificate.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Versions 5.0 to 9.0 of Excel contain various Easter eggs, including a "Hall of Tortured Souls", a *Doom*-like minigame, although since version 10 Microsoft has taken measures to eliminate such undocumented features from their products.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Released in 1995 with Microsoft Office for Windows 95, this is the first major version after Excel 5.0, as there is no Excel 6.0 with all of the Office applications standardizing on the same major version number.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Almost no external changes, but faster and more stable.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Excel 95 contained a hidden *Doom*-like mini-game called "The Hall of Tortured Souls", a series of rooms featuring the names and faces of the developers as an Easter egg.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Included in Office 97 (for x86 and Alpha).
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] This was a major upgrade that introduced the paper clip office assistant and featured standard VBA used instead of internal Excel Basic.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] It introduced the now-removed Natural Language labels.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] This version of Excel includes a flight simulator as an Easter egg.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] This was a minor upgrade but introduced an upgrade to the clipboard where it can hold multiple objects at once.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] The Office Assistant, whose frequent unsolicited appearance in Excel 97 had annoyed many users, became less intrusive.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] A small 3-D game called "Dev Hunter" (inspired by Spy Hunter) was included as an Easter egg.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Included in Office XP with minor enhancements over the previous version.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Included in Office 2003 with minor enhancements over the previous version.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] This release was a major upgrade from the previous version.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Similar to other updated Office products, Excel in 2007 used the new Ribbon menu system.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] This was different from what users were used to, and was met with mixed reactions.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] One study reported fairly good acceptance by users except for highly experienced users and users of word processing applications with a classical WIMP interface, but was less convinced in terms of efficiency and organization.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] However, an online survey reported that a majority of respondents had a negative opinion of the change, with advanced users being "somewhat more negative" than intermediate users, and users reporting a self-estimated reduction in productivity.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Added functionality included Tables, and the SmartArt set of editable business diagrams.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Also added was an improved management of named variables through the *Name Manager*, and much-improved flexibility in formatting graphs, which allow (*x, y*) coordinate labeling and lines of arbitrary weight.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Several improvements to pivot tables were introduced.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Also like other office products, the Office Open XML file formats were introduced, including *.xlsm* for a workbook with macros and *.xlsx* for a workbook without macros.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Specifically, many of the size limitations of previous versions were greatly increased.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] To illustrate, the number of rows was now 1,048,576 (220) and the columns was 16,384 (214; the far-right column is XFD).
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] This changes what is a valid *A1* reference versus a named range.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] This version made more extensive use of multiple cores for the calculation of spreadsheets; however, VBA macros are not handled in parallel and XLL add‑ins were only executed in parallel if they were thread-safe and this was indicated at registration.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Included in Office 2010, this is the next major version after v12.0, as version number 13 was skipped.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Microsoft no longer releases Office or Excel in distinctive versions.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Instead, features are introduced automatically over time.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Thereafter only the approximate dates when features appear can now be given.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Microsoft Office 2024 (the fourth perpetual release of Office 16.0) for the Microsoft Windows and macOS was released on October 1, 2024.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Excel 2.0 for Windows, which was modeled after its Mac GUI-based counterpart, indirectly expanded the installed base of the then-nascent Windows environment.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Excel 2.0 was released a month before Windows 2.0, and the installed base of Windows was so low at that point in 1987 that Microsoft had to bundle a runtime version of Windows 1.0 with Excel 2.0.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Unlike Microsoft Word, there never was a DOS version of Excel.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Excel became the first spreadsheet to allow the user to define the appearance of spreadsheets (fonts, character attributes, and cell appearance).
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] It also introduced intelligent cell re-computation, where only cells dependent on the cell being modified are updated (previous spreadsheet programs recomputed everything all the time or waited for a specific user command).
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Excel introduced auto-fill, the ability to drag and expand the selection box to automatically copy a cell or row contents to adjacent cells or rows, adjusting the copies intelligently by automatically incrementing cell references or contents.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Excel also introduced extensive graphing capabilities.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Excel holds a central place in modern office work: a 2022 survey found that two-thirds of office workers use Excel at least once per hour, spending 38% of their total working time inside the program.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] It is estimated between 750 million and 1.2 billion users access Excel each month.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Because Excel is widely used, it has been attacked by hackers.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] While Excel is not directly exposed to the Internet, if an attacker can get a victim to open a file in Excel, and there is an appropriate security bug in Excel, then the attacker can gain control of the victim's computer.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] UK's GCHQ has a tool named TORNADO ALLEY with this purpose.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] Besides the easter eggs, numerous games have been created or recreated in Excel, such as *Tetris*, *2048*, *Scrabble*, *Yahtzee*, *Angry Birds*, *Pac-Man*, *Civilization*, *Monopoly*, *Battleship*, Blackjack, *Space Invaders*, and others.
[src:vba-macros/microsoft-excel] In 2020, Excel became an esport with the advent of the Financial Modeling World Cup.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Visual Basic for Applications enables building user-defined functions (UDFs), automating processes and accessing Windows API and other low-level functionality through dynamic-link libraries (DLLs).
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] It supersedes and expands on the abilities of earlier application-specific macro programming languages such as Word's WordBASIC.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] It can be used to control many aspects of the host application, including manipulating user interface features, such as menus and toolbars, and working with custom user forms or dialog boxes.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] As its name suggests, VBA is closely related to Visual Basic and uses the Visual Basic Runtime Library.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] However, VBA code normally can only run within a host application, rather than as a standalone program.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] VBA can, however, control one application from another using OLE Automation.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] For example, VBA can automatically create a Microsoft Word report from Microsoft Excel data that Excel collects automatically from polled sensors.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] VBA can use, but not create, ActiveX/COM DLLs, and later versions add support for class modules.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] VBA is built into most Microsoft Office applications, including Office for Mac OS X (except version 2008), and other Microsoft applications, including Microsoft MapPoint and Microsoft Visio.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] VBA is also implemented, at least partially, in applications published by companies other than Microsoft, including ArcGIS, AutoCAD, Collabora Online, CorelDraw, Kingsoft Office, LibreOffice, Softmaker Office, SolidWorks, WordPerfect, and UNICOM System Architect (which supports VBA 7.1).
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] When personal computers were initially released in the 1970s and 1980s, they typically included a version of BASIC so that customers could write their own programs.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Microsoft's first products were BASIC compilers and interpreters, and the company distributed versions of BASIC with MS-DOS (versions 1.0 through 6.0) and developed follow-on products that offered more features and capabilities (QuickBASIC and BASIC Professional Development System).
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] In 1989, Bill Gates sketched out Microsoft's plans to use BASIC as a universal language to embellish or alter the performance of a range of software applications on microcomputers.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] He also revealed that the installed base of active BASIC programmers was four million users, and that BASIC was used three times more frequently than any other language on PCs.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] When Visual Basic was released in 1991, it seemed logical to use Visual Basic as the universal programming language for Windows applications.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Until that time, each Microsoft application had its own macro language or automation technique, and the tools were largely incompatible.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] The first Microsoft application to debut VBA was Microsoft Excel 5.0 in 1993, based on Microsoft Visual Basic 3.0.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] This spurred the development of numerous custom business applications, and the decision was made to release VBA in a range of products.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Windows users learned about the changes through user groups, books, and magazines.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Early computer books that introduced VBA programming skills include Reed Jacobsen's *Microsoft Excel Visual Basic for Windows 95 Step by Step* (Microsoft Press, 1995) and Michael Halvorson and Chris Kinata's *Microsoft Word 97 Visual Basic Step by Step* (Microsoft Press, 1997).
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Code written in VBA is compiled to Microsoft P-Code (pseudo-code), a proprietary intermediate language, which the host applications (Access, Excel, Word, Outlook, and PowerPoint) store as a separate stream in COM Structured Storage files (e.g., `.doc` or `.xls`) independent of the document streams.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] The intermediate code is then executed by a virtual machine (hosted by the host application).
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Compatibility ends with Visual Basic version 6; VBA is incompatible with Visual Basic .NET (VB.NET).
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] VBA is proprietary to Microsoft and, apart from the COM interface, is not an open standard.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Interaction with the host application uses OLE Automation.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Typically, the host application provides a type library and application programming interface (API) documentation which document how VBA programs can interact with the application.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] This documentation can be examined from inside the VBA development environment using its Object Browser.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Visual Basic for Applications programs which are written to use the OLE Automation interface of one application cannot be used to automate a different application, even if that application hosts the Visual Basic runtime, because the OLE Automation interfaces will be different.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] For example, a VBA program written to automate Microsoft Word cannot be used with a different word processor, even if that word processor hosts VBA.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Conversely, multiple applications can be automated from the one host by creating Application objects within the VBA code.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] References to the different libraries must be created within the VBA client before any of the methods, objects, etc. become available to use in the application.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] This is achieved through what is referred to as Early or Late Binding.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] These application objects create the OLE link to the application when they are first created.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Commands to the different applications must be done explicitly through these application objects in order to work correctly.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] VBA programs can be attached to a menu button, a macro, a keyboard shortcut, or an OLE/COM event, such as the opening of a document in the application.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] The language provides a user interface in the form of UserForms, which can host ActiveX controls for added functionality.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Inter-process communication automation includes the Dynamic Data Exchange (DDE) and RealTimeData (RTD) which allows calling a Component Object Model (COM) automation server for dynamic or realtime financial or scientific data.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] As with any common programming language, VBA macros can be created with malicious intent.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Using VBA, most of the security features lie in the hands of the user, not the author.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] The VBA host application options are accessible to the user.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] The user who runs any document containing VBA macros can preset the software with user preferences.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] End-users can protect themselves from attack by disabling macros from running in an application or by granting permission for a document to run VBA code only if they are sure that the source of the document can be trusted.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] In February 2022, Microsoft announced its plan to block VBA macros in files downloaded from the Internet by default in a variety of Office apps due to their widespread use to spread malware.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] A risk with using VBA macros, such as in Microsoft Office applications, is exposure to viruses.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Risks stem from factors including ease of writing macros which decreases the skill required the write a malicious macro and that typical document sharing practices allow for a virus to spread quickly.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] A system macro – one that provides a core operation – can be redefined.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] This allows for significant flexibility, but also is a risk that hackers can exploit to access the document and its host computer without the user's knowledge or consent.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] For example, a hacker could replace the built-in core functionality macros such as AutoExec, AutoNew, AutoClose, AutoOpen, AutoExit with malicious versions.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] A malicious macro could be configured to run when the user presses a common keyboard shortcut such as Ctrl+B which is normally for bold font.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] A type of macro virus that cuts and pastes the text of a document in the macro.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] The macro could be invoked with the Auto-open macro so that the text would be re-created when the document (empty) is opened.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] The user will not notice that the document is empty.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] The macro could also convert only some parts of the text in order to be less noticeable.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Removing macros from the document manually or by using an anti-virus program could lead to a loss of content in the document.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] So, in order to implement macros viruses which can change its contents, hackers have to create another macro which fulfills the task to modify the content of the virus.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] However, this type of macro viruses is not widespread.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Indeed, hackers frequently choose to do macro viruses because they are easy and quick to implement.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Making a polymorphic macro requires a lot of knowledge of the WordBasic language (it needs the advanced functionalities) and more time than a "classic" macro virus.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Even if a hacker were to make a polymorphic macro, the polymorphism needs to be done, so, the document needs to update and the update can be visible to a user.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] During replication, a macro can create do-nothing macros.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] But this idea can be combined with polymorphic macros, so macros are not necessarily do-nothing; each macro invokes the next one, so they can be arranged in a chain.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] In such a case, if they are not all removed during a disinfection, some destructive payload is activated.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Such an attack can crash the winword processor with an internal error.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Since Winword 6.0, the number of macros per template is limited to 150, so the attack is limited, too, but can still be very annoying.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Macro viruses can, in some cases, interact between themselves.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] If two viruses are executed at the same time, both of them can modify the source code of each other.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] So, it results a new virus which can not be recognize by the anti-viruses software.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] But the result is totally random: the macro virus can be more infectious or less infectious, depending upon which part of the virus has been changed.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] However, when the 'mating' is unintentional, the resulting macro virus has more chances to be less infectious.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Indeed, in order to replicate itself, it has to know the commands in the source code, but, if it is changed with a random scheme, the macro can not replicate itself.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Nevertheless, it is possible to do such macros intentionally (it is different from polymorphic macros viruses which must use another macro to change their contents) in order to increase the infectivity of the two viruses.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] In the example of the article, the macro virus *Colors* infected a document, but another infected the user's system before : the macro virus *Concept*.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Both of these viruses use the command *AutoOpen*, so, at first, the macro virus *Colors* was detected but the command *AutoOpen* in it was the command of the macro virus *Concept*.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Moreover, when *Concept* duplicates itself, it is unencrypted, but the command in the virus *Colors* was encrypted (Colors encrypt its commands).
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] So, replication of the macro virus *Concept* results in the hybridation of this macro virus (which had infected the user's system first) and *Colors*.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] The "hybrid" could replicate itself only if *AutoOpen* were not executed; indeed this command comes from *Concept*, but the body of the hybrid is *Colors*, so that create some conflicts.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Fortunately, this type of macro virus is rare (more than the polymorphic macro viruses, one may not even exist), indeed, creating two (or more) which can interact with each other and not reduce the virility (rather reinforce it) is complicated.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Macros can be designed to modify existing Macros, such a tool would allow one to create a new virus by modifying an existing one.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] This is difficult to do with executable files.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] But it is very simple for macro viruses, since the source code of macros are always available.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] In a similar manner to polymorphic macros, a macro can perform modifications to all macros present in the document.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Considering this, just a few modifications could create a macro virus mutator, and thereby quickly create several thousands of known viruses.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Most macros viruses are stand-alone; they do not depend on other macros (for the infectious part of the virus, not for the replication for some viruses), but some macros viruses do.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] When launched, they check other macros (viruses or not), and append their contents to them.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] In this way, all of the macros became viruses.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] But, this type of macro can not be spread as quickly as stand-alone macros.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Indeed, it depends on other macros, so, without them, the virus can not be spread.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] So, parasitic macros often are hybrid: they are stand alone and they can infect other macros.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] This kind of macro virus poses real problems to the virus-specific anti-virus; in fact, they change the content of other viruses, so that accurate detection is not possible.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] There are different types of anti-virus (or scanners), one is the heuristic analysis anti-virus which interprets or emulates macros.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Indeed, to examine all branches of macros require a NP-complete complexity (using backtracking), so in this case, the analysis of one document (which contains macros) would take too much time.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Interpreting or emulating a macro would lead to either false positive errors or in macro viruses not detected.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] So, like the heuristic analysis, this can lead to false positives errors, due to the fact that this type of anti-virus checks the whole document.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] The last type of anti-virus seen will be the virus-specific scanner.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] It searches the signature of viruses, so, the type of anti-virus is weaker than the previous ones.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Indeed, the viruses detected by virus-specific scanners are just the ones known by the software producers (so, more updates are needed than in other types of scanners).
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Moreover, this type of anti-virus is weak against morphing viruses (cf.section above).
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] If a macro virus change its content (so, its signature), it cannot be detected any more by the virus-specific scanners, even if it is the same virus doing the same actions.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Its signature does not match the one declared in the virus scanner.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Additional to the responsibility of the anti-virus is the user's responsibility: if a potential macro virus is detected, the user can choose what to do with it: ignore it, quarantine it or destroy it, but the last option is the most dangerous.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] The anti-virus can activate some destructive macro viruses which destroy some data when they are deleted by the anti-virus.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] So, both virus scanners and users are responsible for the security and the integrity of the documents/computer.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Moreover, even if the anti-virus is not optimal in the virus detection, most macro viruses are detected and the progression in virus detection improves but with creation of new macro viruses.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] As of July 1, 2007, Microsoft no longer offers VBA distribution licenses to new customers.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Microsoft intended to add .NET-based languages to the current version of VBA ever since the release of the .NET Framework, of which versions 1.0 and 1.1 included a scripting runtime technology named *Script for the .NET Framework*.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Visual Studio .NET 2002 and 2003 SDK contained a separate scripting IDE called *Visual Studio for Applications* (VSA) that supported VB.NET.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] One of its significant features was that the interfaces to the technology were available via Active Scripting (VBScript and JScript), allowing even .NET-unaware applications to be scripted via .NET languages.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Microsoft dropped VBA support for Microsoft Office 2008 for Mac.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] VBA was restored in Microsoft Office for Mac 2011.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Microsoft said that it has no plan to remove VBA from the Windows version of Office.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] With Office 2010, Microsoft introduced VBA7, which contains a true pointer data type: LongPtr.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] This allows referencing 64-bit address space.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] This did not affect the 32-bit version Office 2010.
[src:vba-macros/visual-basic-for-applications] Microsoft eventually released a 64-bit version of MSComCtl with the July 27th, 2017 update to Office 2016.
